        "header": "Appendix BLifting Network Details",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2605.01234/2605.01234v1/x3.png",
                "caption": "Figure SM1.Schematic illustration of the Disentangled Context Embedding (DCE). Table Keypoints{k→i}i=012\\{\\vec{k}_{i}\\}_{i=0}^{12}and detected 2D ball coordinatesr→2D\\vec{r}_{\\text{2D}}are projected to higher dimensional vectors. If a ball is not correctly detected, a learnable interpolation tokenτint\\tau_{\\text{int}}is used instead of the ball vector. Finally, both vectors are concatenated and the final location tokenlnl_{n}is computed.",
                "position": 2448
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2605.01234/2605.01234v1/x4.png",
                "caption": "Figure SM2.Schematic illustration of the Lifting Network.\nFirst, the detected ball positionsr→2​D​(tn)\\vec{r}_{2D}(t_{n})and table keypoints{k→i}i=012\\{\\vec{k}_{i}\\}_{i=0}^{12}are embedded to obtain the sequence of location tokens{ln}n=0N−1\\{l_{n}\\}_{n=0}^{N-1}.\nThe lift network transforms these tokens and each output is further processed by a Spin Head to obtain the spin vectorω→​(tn)\\vec{\\omega}(t_{n})and Trajectory Head to obtain the 3D positionr→3D​(tn)\\vec{r}_{\\text{3D}}(t_{n})for each timesteptnt_{n}. We refer to(Kienzleet al.,2026)for further information on the transformer architecture.",
                "position": 2470
            }
        ]
    },
